   =20
 =20
On the other hand with a public company you have more latitude. We  talked =
in May about a Hindenburg Research short report about Carl Icahn=E2=80=99s =
company, Icahn Enterprises LP; Hindenburg wrote:In brief, Icahn has been us=
ing money taken in from new investors to pay out dividends to old investors=
. Such ponzi-like economic structures are sustainable only to the extent th=
at new money is willing to risk being the last one =E2=80=9Cholding the bag=
=E2=80=9D.The idea is that Icahn Enterprises is more or less a hedge fund i=
n the form of a public company; you can calculate the net asset value of it=
s holdings, but its stock price does not necessarily have to track that NAV=
. And Icahn Enterprises pays a quarterly cash dividend, but that cash divid=
end is not directly tied to changes in its NAV: The company can pay a consi=
stent $2 cash dividend whether its investments go up or down. The investmen=
ts have largely gone down in recent years, but the dividend has stayed stab=
le, and the company has funded the dividend in part by selling new shares. =
Because the dividend is high and stable, and because Icahn is a celebrity, =
the shares trade at well above net asset value, which means that this trade=
 can work: Your stock trades at 3 times NAV, you sell stock for $100, you h=
ave $100 in new cash, that $100 of cash increases the stock value by $300 (=
3 times NAV), and you spend $50 of it paying a dividend to your shareholder=
s to keep the stock price high.But once someone points it out, it doesn=E2=
=80=99t work as well. The stock is down more than 50% since the Hindenburg =
report,  and now:=C2=A0Carl Icahn slashed his company=E2=80=99s quarterly p=
ayouts in half and pledged to =E2=80=9Cstick to our knitting=E2=80=9D in an=
other substantive move acknowledging complaints raised by short-seller Hind=
enburg Research earlier this year.Shares of Icahn Enterprises LP fell as mu=
ch as 37% in New York on Friday after the firm said it will pay out $1 per =
depositary unit, down from the previous $2 a unit.The company=E2=80=99s sec=
ond-quarter loss more than doubled from a year earlier, and Icahn pledged a=
 =E2=80=9Creset=E2=80=9D with the firm reducing its short bets and focusing=
 on the activism that made him a famed investor. =E2=80=A6Icahn blamed the =
=E2=80=9Cmisleading and self-serving Hindenburg report=E2=80=9D for its lat=
est struggles, while proving prescient one of the short seller=E2=80=99s ce=
ntral claims: that the firm=E2=80=99s dividend was unsustainable. IEP has b=
een under pressure since May, when Nate Anderson=E2=80=99s firm leveled a s=
eries of accusations against it, claiming, among other things, that it was =
over-leveraged and trading at an excessively steep premium to its net asset=
 value.=E2=80=9COn May 2nd, we predicted that =E2=80=98Icahn Enterprises wi=
ll eventually cut or eliminate its dividend entirely, barring a miracle tur=
naround in investment performance,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Hindenburg said on the=
 X platform Friday. =E2=80=9CToday, $IEP reported further investment losses=
 and slashed its dividend by 50%. We remain short.=E2=80=9DRoughly speaking=
, Icahn Enterprises trades on its expected future dividends. If the dividen=
d has been $2 per quarter for years, and you have no other information, a r=
easonable guess would be that the future dividends will also be $2 per quar=
ter. If someone just comes along and=C2=A0says, noisily, =E2=80=9Cthis divi=
dend is unsustainable,=E2=80=9D then you might update your expectations abo=
ut future dividends. And then the price will drop and the dividend really w=
ill be unsustainable. Meanwhile:Gautam Adani, Jack Dorsey, Carl Icahn. Nate=
 Anderson has picked them off one by one.In mere months this year, he erase=
d as much as $99 billion of their combined wealth while knocking $173 billi=
on off the value of their publicly traded companies. In an era when promine=
nt short sellers have retreated from the limelight =E2=80=94 fretting lawsu=
its, short squeezes and government probes =E2=80=94 the deft researcher has=
 emerged as the gutsiest bear around. Allies say he=E2=80=99s risking civil=
 suits, physical attacks and potentially even overseas arrest.The surprise =
is that Anderson, 39, who runs tiny Hindenburg Research with a team of roug=
hly a dozen researchers, probably reaped relatively small profits from thos=
e fights.Take his report on May 2, accusing Icahn=E2=80=99s holding company=
, Icahn Enterprises, of overvaluing assets. Within four weeks, the stock=E2=
=80=99s plunge erased $17 billion of the billionaire=E2=80=99s wealth. Yet =
the combined gain for all investors who shorted the shares before the repor=
t would have been about $56 million if they timed their exits perfectly, ac=
cording to data from S3 Partners. And that=E2=80=99s not counting the cost =
of setting up the bets.I mean in general if you think a company is a fraud =
and decide to bet against it, and you are right and its value collapses, yo=
u should not expect a very efficient=C2=A0transfer of wealth from the compa=
ny to you. If you could erase $99 billion of corporate founder wealth by ac=
tivist short selling, and=C2=A0take all of it yourself, more people would d=
o it.
