om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">All weather alpha</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you run an investment fund, each mo=
nth your fund will either go up (if you made good investments) or down (if =
you made bad ones). If it goes up, you report a gain to your investors, and=
 they are happy. If it goes down ...=C2=A0well, look, that is obviously not=
 what you intended. You are a good investment manager and you will undoubte=
dly make the fund go up again; you got this month wrong, but you=C2=A0will =
pick good investments from now on.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If=
 you think about it, really<em>=C2=A0</em>your fund hasn=E2=80=99t lost any=
 value at all: Sure the stocks in the fund have gone down, but the expected=
 long-term value of the fund has <em>not</em> gone down, because you will w=
ork extra hard to make it go all the way back up again next month.=C2=A0And=
 really<em>=C2=A0</em>the accounting statements of the fund should reflect =
that fact, so as not to unnecessarily scare or annoy your investors: The ac=
counting statements should record a loss on your stocks, fully offset =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>than offset, even =E2=80=94=C2=A0by a new as=
set, your promise to make the money back again. The net asset value of your=
 fund consists of (1) the stocks in the fund=C2=A0<em>plus=C2=A0</em>(2) yo=
ur promise to make up any losses, and as (1) shrinks (2) grows. So really t=
he net asset value of your fund can=C2=A0<em>never=C2=A0</em>go down.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ahahahaha no, this is wrong, this is not the way=
 accounting works, or investing, not at all. This is the way Ponzi schemes =
work! But I guess you could talk yourself into it. More to the point, the g=
uy=C2=A0running a fund called EIA All Weather Alpha Fund I LP <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32321698.266412/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjMvMzMtMTEyMTgucGRm/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB09693ef5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> allegedly=C2=A0talked his fund administr=
ator</a>, Theorem Fund Services LLC,=C2=A0into it:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During February and March 2018, the Advisers continued=
 to lose money trading on the Third Party Platform, losing an additional $3=
42,000. TFS received trading statements showing these losses and TFS accoun=
ted for these losses as losses of the Fund. TFS then provided the NAV and I=
nvestor Statements to the Advisers for review. Upon reviewing the NAV and t=
he Investor Statements that evidenced the losses, the Advisers instructed T=
FS to change the accounting for the losses. Specifically, the Advisers inst=
ructed TFS, and it agreed, to record an expense reimbursement for all losse=
s from the Advisers=E2=80=99 trading as an asset, specifically, a receivabl=
e =E2=80=9Cdue from the Manager (EIA),=E2=80=9D which offset the effect of =
the loss, resulting in no reduction to the Fund=E2=80=99s NAV. The Advisers=
 further instructed, and TFS agreed, that going forward, any losses from th=
e Advisers=E2=80=99 trading would be treated as an increase to the receivab=
le due from the manager (EIA). At no point was EIA actually liable to the F=
und for losses.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">TFS carried out these instr=
uctions during the remainder of its engagement with EIA and treated the Fun=
d=E2=80=99s trading losses, which continued to grow over time, not as losse=
s and a reduction to the Fund=E2=80=99s NAV, but instead as a receivable du=
e from EIA with no related reduction to the Fund=E2=80=99s NAV. TFS did not=
 evaluate whether this was appropriate, determine the collectability of the=
 receivable, or verify that any legal requirement of repayment existed. TFS=
 accepted the Advisers=E2=80=99 word that the Advisers were legally liable =
to reimburse the losses (which they in fact were not) and thus the losses w=
ere due from EIA and used this treatment to calculate each monthly NAV. As =
a result, TFS prepared and disseminated Investor Statements containing mate=
rially overvalued equity balances throughout the Relevant Period because th=
e balances were never decreased or showed any losses. Upon receiving the In=
vestor Statements, two investors invested additional money in the Fund.</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is from today=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0US Securities and Exchange Commission=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/32321698.266412/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXd=
zL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMy0xNDg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB84cbda96" itempro=
